Agriculture, forestry, and other land use account for an estimated 23\% 
of anthropogenic greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions~\cite{SRCCL2019}. 
Agriculture has strong links to land use, which is the focus of 
Chapter \ref{chap:land_use_urban_planning}.
It began to be evident in Chapters~\ref{chap:households} and~\ref{chap:transportation}
that land use has strong sustainability implications. 
Those hints will become much more concrete and explicit in this chapter and 
in Chapter~\ref{chap:land_use_urban_planning}. 
Agriculture is \emph{the} major use to which humans put the land.
It is estimated that 71\% of ice-free land is used for agricultural purposes:
12\% for crops, 
37\% for pasture, and 
22\% for timber production in forests~\cite{SRCCL2019}.

In addition to land use and GHG emissions, agriculture has another 
major implication for sustainability: humans cannot live without food.
Agriculture does provide some nonfood products such as cotton, flax (for linen),
flowers, and leather.
However, this chapter will mostly focus on food products, in part because the 
sustainability characteristics that apply to food agriculture also apply to 
nonfood agriculture.
Food is the only source of \emph{energy} humans can use to pursue lives of work, service, 
and play.
Moreover, food is the source of \emph{material} inputs (``essential nutrients'') 
humans need to grow and maintain our bodies.
By definition, 
and in contrast to some of the examples mentioned in Section~\ref{sec:recycling},
``food'' is \emph{not} a substitutable resource.
Although humans can exist on a wide variety of diets, we can't directly metabolize 
nonfood items, such as wood, cellulose, sunlight, or petroleum.

Food doesn't appear on plates magically, out of nowhere.
It arrives on our plates through a network of 
natural and human-created transformation processes\index{transformation processes!food}
that convert solar energy\index{energy!solar}
into available, ingestible energy\index{energy!ingestible}.
This network is often called ``agriculture.''\index{agriculture}
The combined economic value
of the agriculture, forestry, and fishing industries is 
about 1\% of GDP for the U.S.\ 
and about 3.5\% of GDP worldwide~\cite{World-Bank-agriculture:aa}.
However, the importance of agriculture goes far beyond its economic value.
Without agriculture, none of us would be here today!
This chapter presents key information about the food system and explores its 
sustainability challenges.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Demand for agriculture}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Food consumption is rather predictable, because food requirements 
(measured in food calories, for example)
scale linearly with population. 
Over a long period of time, at least since 1870, 
when such things were first measured, 
the amount people eat, in pounds of food per day, 
has been relatively constant~\cite{Gordon2016}, which is unsurprising, since
there is a fundamental, biological limit to the amount our bellies can hold.
However, in the U.S., there has been about a 22\% increase in calories consumed 
per person per day since 1967~\cite{Gordon2016}.
The trend has also been toward a more varied diet that includes more fresh foods.
This trend towards a richer, more varied diet is repeated across the world as
affluence rises.
Thus, the global demand for food has two main drivers:
population~\Pparen{} is the primary driver of demand for agriculture, and
affluence~\Aparen{} is the secondary driver.

As mentioned in Section~\ref{sec:PCbalance}, consumption and production are balanced,
particularly for food, in part because food spoils and humans prefer fresh food.
Sometimes, future food \emph{supply} is cited as being a sustainability concern, usually on
the basis of past and current food production. 
However, because of the consumption/production balance, past and current production
is a poor indicator of future food production capacity.
Food is one of the few things humans \emph{can't} do without.
Rising affluence (Figure~\ref{fig:AffluenceGraph-Nordhaus}) means there are lots
of things we could (and would) do without before we would give up food.
(The share of wealth spent on food goes down as affluence rises, meaning food becomes
relatively cheaper as economies develop.)
Furthermore, Section~\ref{sec:malthus_ehrlich_simon} indirectly suggests humanity 
will continue to have resources for food production, even if population grows substantially.
Therefore, total global food production should not be expected to be a major sustainability
challenge.
(Despite the fact that hunger continues to be an issue in the world today, current food
production is generally acknowledged to be adequate.
Instead, there are distribution problems due to such factors as poverty, government
corruption, and oppression.)

Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX} indicates reductions in agricultural impacts on the 
environment, in the absence of a falling population or affluence 
(Section~\ref{sec:reducing_c}), can only come from reducing one of the remaining two terms,
the resource intensity of economic activity~\Rparen{} or the impact of resources~\Xparen{}.
The next section explores sustainability challenges in agriculture, which arise
from extracting resources from the ecosystem and/or producing more waste(s) than the 
ecosystem can absorb.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Sustainability challenges in agriculture}
\label{sec:ag_sust_challenges}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

When considering whether an activity is sustainable, resource depletion and impacts
produced are key questions.
That is, have the ecosystem's provisioning and/or support services been exceeded?
(See Section~\ref{sec:ecosystem_services}.)
For example, Section~\ref{sec:electric_vehicles} considered internal combustion
engine (ICE) vehicles and electric vehicles (EVs).
A reliable sustainability comparison depends on an accurate accounting of inputs and outputs.
Section~\ref{sec:electric_vehicles} considered vehicle emissions
while in use, the energy and mineral resources used to create each vehicle, and
the source of the power for each vehicle; 
see Figure~\ref{fig:auto_gwp}. 
Each of these three accountings
(direct emissions;
vehicle emissions and the materials used to make the vehicle; or
vehicle emissions, minerals in the vehicle, 
\emph{and} power or fuel generation)
give a different nuance to the sustainability impacts
of vehicle manufacturing, use, and disposal.

In a similar manner,
defining appropriate inputs and outputs for agricultural sustainability 
is a key consideration.
Recall the definitions of \emph{weak} and \emph{strong} sustainability from 
Section~\ref{sec:strong_weak_sust}.
% and the concept of ecosystem provisioning services from Section~\ref{sec:ecosystem_services}.
Strong sustainability requires not using renewable resources 
faster than they can regenerate
(Section~\ref{sec:what_is_sustainability}).
Choosing the right inputs and outputs for agriculture is demonstrated
by considering soil fertility. 
Soil fertility is a renewable provisioning service (Chapter~\ref{chap:planetary_boundaries})
of the ecosystem.
If agricultural practices decrease soil fertility, 
agriculture can not be considered strongly sustainable.
If agriculture depends on a nonrenewable resource, 
such as phosphate fertilizers, it cannot be considered strongly sustainable.
If agriculture is rapidly depleting soil fertility
such that the soil will be unusable in less than 50~years,
agriculture is not weakly sustainable.
The sections below examine the sustainability characteristics of several different
aspects of agriculture.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Soil and water} %% Agricultural use of land
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Soil and water are the two most important inputs for agriculture.
As mentioned earlier, most of the usable land in the world 
is put to agricultural uses. 
Similarly, agriculture accounts for approximately 70\% of human freshwater use.
The paragraphs below examine a variety of unsustainable practices related to human 
use of land and water.


%..............................
\paragraph{Loss of soil fertility} 
%..............................

Not all soils are rich in the nutrients needed by plants to grow, but
top soil contains the organic matter needed by plants.
However, top soil can be lost by erosion due to the action of wind and/or water.
Most erosion results from wind or water action on tilled soils, that is,
where the land has been plowed to expose bare soil.
Some examples include the great Dust Bowl in the U.S.\ in the 1930s
and the phenomenon called the ``Yellow Wind'' or ``Asian dust,'' where fine
soil particles are carried from China, Mongolia, and Kazakhstan to East Asia and 
sometimes across the Pacific Ocean to the U.S.
Some places in the Great Plains have lost of several feet of topsoil.
For example, a survey in Minot, North Dakota taken in 1900 found 40 cm of black
topsoil.
In 2017, the area had no black topsoil; its soil was light gray~\cite{Arnason:2017ug}.
Loss of top soil reduces the productivity 
(in dollars of output per acre) of farmland.
Many arid and semi-arid regions are experiencing \emph{desertification} caused
by a combination of climate change and poor agricultural practices.
The rate of erosion and runoff increases exponentially with the loss of vegetation 
cover~\cite{Geeson2003}. 
Unprotected soil surfaces are eroded by wind and water to leave unproductive 
inorganic subsoils that get baked by the sun into a hardpan.
Soil fertility can also be degraded by practices that withdraw key nutrients from the 
soil faster than they can be regenerated.
For instance, about 8\% of the carbon in soils has been lost over the last 12,000
years~\cite{Sanderman2017}.

In contrast, 
sustainable agriculture at least maintains, and hopefully builds, soil fertility.
Soil fertility and agricultural productivity 
can be enhanced with fertilizers and/or agrichemicals.
The most common fertilizers contain nitrogen, phosphorous, and potassium. 
Agrichemicals include herbicides, pesticides, and fungicides. 
To the extent that any of these are derived from nonrenewable feedstocks, such as 
fossil fuels, their use is not strongly sustainable.
Phosphate fertilizers are necessary for high crop yields, but
they originate from (nonrenewable) mineral deposits.
On the other hand, about half of the fertilizer used globally is animal manure, 
which is a renewable resource. 
Animal manure could be a sustainable fertilizer, if the animals are raised sustainably,
for instance, if their feed is sustainably raised.
A sustainability challenge associated soil use is “how can we maintain soil fertility
in the long term without fertilizers based on nonrenewable resources?''


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\paragraph{Water---quantity and quality}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Plants need water to grow.
Currently, much of agricultural irrigation is not sustainable because water is being
extracted from aquifers faster than the natural regeneration rate.
If aquifers are exhausted, future humans won't have water for nourishment or bathing.
Overuse of water is not limited to subsurface water, like the Ogallala aquifer; 
see \ref{question:ogallala}. 
Surface water is also being overused for agriculture.
One particularly notable example is the (formerly) Aral Sea, which has all but disappeared
due to diversion of its water for irrigation.
Another example is the Colorado River, which supplies water to 12\% of the U.S.\ population,
supports 15\% of U.S.\ crop output, and 13\% of U.S.\ livestock production~\cite{UWMCWP2014}. 
%% https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lYvQNon4aLg&t=804s
%% https://feedingourselvesthirsty.ceres.org/regional-analysis/colorado-river
%% https://uwm.edu/centerforwaterpolicy/wp-content/uploads/sites/170/2013/10/Colorado_Agriculture_Final.pdf
Because of diversions for agriculture (70--80\%) and to supply municipalities with drinking 
water (15\%), the Colorado River mouth is dry; 
it no longer flows into the Sea of Cortez.

Agricultural activities also result in water pollution of surface water and ground water.
For example, the city of Toledo, Ohio draws its drinking water from Lake Erie.
Since the 1990s, Lake Erie has been subject to ``blooms'' of toxic cyanobacteria
fueled by fertilizer run off.
Six people got sick in 2013.
In 2014, 110 people got sick and the municipal water supply to 400,000 people was shut down.
Moreover, Lake Erie and the Maumee River that feeds it were unsafe for human skin contact.
Blooms occurred again in 2017 and 2019~\cite{Rogener:2020wi}.
Animal manure can also contaminate waterways. Ick.

A sustainability challenge associated agricultural use of water is “how can we 
maintain sufficient sources of clean water for agriculture and (direct) human use?''


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Energy}
\label{sec:food_energy_return_ratios}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 
The energy input to agriculture ranges from human and animal 
labor to electricity and hydrocarbon fuels, either fossil fuels or biofuels.
Energy is used at all stages of agriculture, from preparing the ground to sow crops,
to harvesting, storage, transportation, cooking, and disposal of food.
Because food is humanity's energy source, we should consider its energy
return on investment (EROI, defined in Section~\ref{sec:masterE})\index{EROI}.
When EROI~>~1, food is an energy source for humans, that is,
we obtain more energy from the food than it took to get the food.
When EROI~<~1, we spend more energy obtaining the food than we get 
from the food. 
Since we have to have food, it is worth spending energy on.
Whether spending more energy on food than we get from it is sustainable or not
depends on where the energy for agriculture comes from. 


