\paragraph{CO$_2$}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

One source of GHG emissions in food and agriculture 
is the food-delivery system.
Figure~\ref{fig:food_ghg} shows GHG emissions from the various stages of food
distribution and preparation. 
The amount of CO$_2$ released is proportional to the amount of energy used.
Figure~\ref{fig:FoodEmissionsPerMcal} shows equivalent CO$_2$ emissions per Mcal of food.
(Foods with low feed-to-food efficiency tend to have higher GHG emissions;
see Figure~\ref{fig:FoodToFeedEfficiency}.)
However, by itself Figure~\ref{fig:FoodEmissionsPerMcal} is not terribly informative.
We don't eat equal calories of each food.
We need a balanced diet that provides all of our essential
nutrients.
Figure~\ref{fig:GHG_food} shows what individual foods contribute to overall food
emissions (but not what quantity of each are consumed).
Taken together, Figures~\ref{fig:food_ghg}--\ref{fig:GHG_food} 
paint a suggestive picture of agricultural CO$_2$ emissions.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\paragraph{CH$_4$}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

One tonne of methane has the same global-warming potential as twenty five tonnes 
of CO$_2$---methane is a very potent GHG.
Methane is about 10\% of U.S.\ GHG emissions. 
Of this 10\%, about 39\% comes from agriculture, 40\% comes from energy and transportation,
and 21\% comes from landfills and wastewater treatment~\cite{USEPA:2021uj}.
Agricultural emissions are almost entirely from enteric digestion and manure management,
with a small amount (6\%) coming from rice cultivation.
Enteric digestion refers to the production of methane in an animal's digestion.
The amount of methane produced depends on the quality of the animal's feed.
Seventy two percent of methane from enteric digestion comes from beef cattle; 24\% is from 
dairy cattle~\cite{USEPA:2021uj}.
Methane from manure management tends to come from liquified manure treatment, which
is often the preferred method for concentrated animal populations.
Dairy cattle account for 51.3\% of methane from manure and swine account for 37\%~\cite{USEPA:2021uj}.

A sustainability challenge associated agricultural GHG emissions is “how can we 
eliminate GHG emissions from agriculture?''


