\section{Sustainability transitions in agriculture}
\label{sec:food_ag_efficiency}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

The section describes ways in which agriculture should become more sustainable.
Environmental impacts from agricultural activity could be eliminated if 
agriculture itself were eliminated. 
However, this would result in undesirable effects on human population; see the epigraph
at the top of this chapter.
Instead, this section investigates ways agriculture can become more sustainable,
while still meeting human needs (caloric and nutritional) and wants (variety).
In other words, we prefer to preserve (total) agricultural output with a ``long tail''
of crops and products, and a robust trade from region-to-region and even internationally.
Some rearrangement of production is contemplated, for example less meat and more 
legumes.

To be more sustainable, agriculture must reduce its intensity (of resource use
and impacts produced) or, inversely, it must increase its productivity.
To be strongly sustainable, agriculture must increase soil fertility without extracting minerals and 
water from the environment at rates greater than minerals and water naturally 
regenerate.
The sections below examine agricultural efficacy and soil regeneration in more detail.


