\section{Summary}
\label{sec:food_transitions}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Agricultural sustainability challenges include unsustainable land-use practices
that degrade soil fertility, require unsustainable mineral inputs, and harm the 
land's ability to sequester carbon.
In today's economy, 
agriculture is an energy sink rather than an energy source, 
requiring the unsustainable input of fossil fuels.
Lastly, agricultural practices are the source of a significant GHG emissions.
However, food is a basic human need; it is one of the few things we absolutely 
cannot do without. 
Therefore, it is crucially important to make choices, individually and corporately,
that result in a sustainable agricultural system. 
These choices must result in higher productivities for the agricultural system and
practices that preserve and enhance soil fertility.
